Before the Coronavirus outbreak, the CNY was strengthening due mainly to the Phase 1 trade deal with the United States. It reached a high of 6.8597 per USD on January 13th, 2020. China has also been under pressure from the USA to reduce its control over its currency. However, with the outbreak growing and China increasingly becoming closed off from the world economically, the CNY weakened some to a 2020 low almost 7.0000 per USD in early February. This is a difficult forecast without any precedent. China's GDP is forecasted to fall to 4.5% growth according to a Reuters poll of Chinese economists (likely biased high). If the official numbers are this low or even lower than I expect the CNY to weaken to above 7.0000 per dollar. If the outbreak is quickly contained and GDP growth is between 4.5% and 6% I expect the CNY to stay fairly stable at just under 7.0000/USD. The potential of the coronavirus outbreak getting worse and GDP growth to be very low cannot be ruled out hence the 7% chance of the CNY dropping all the way down to 8.000/USD. https://www.bloomberg.com/quote/USDCNY:CUR https://www.thebalance.com/dollar-to-yuan-conversion-and-history-3306089 https://www.macrotrends.net/2575/us-dollar-yuan-exchange-rate-historical-chart https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-economy-poll/chinese-economy-clobbered-by-coronavirus-but-set-to-recover-soon-reuters-poll-idUSKBN20801H

This one is tricky, because as already pointed out by several forecasters, the RMB is not freely exchangeable. Instead it moves within a daily peg.

Some assumptions that went into this forecast: - This is not a typical foreign exchange rate question as they have been asked on GJO before - the CNY is in a grey area of freely traded vs pegged. Therefore, I think approaches like frequencies of previous closes or models using previous volatility are limited (nevertheless, for lack of alternatives, I will be using them at least for some scenarios in this forecast) - To what extend the People's Bank of China will allow the CNY to weaken against the USD is a political question and should be seen in the context of the trade/tariff dispute between China and the US [1]
Over last five years - rough guidelines = low $6.19 March '15 / high Sept '19 $7.19 Influencing factors - China's monetary policy has shifted - trade war strategy - internal market needs
Still volatile

The appetite for a trade deal has increased since a prolonged trade war presents a lose-lose outcome for the US -China negotiations. After "Phase I" is signed (the expectation is this will occur sometime in November), even if no other deals are signed for several months afterwards, the global economy, US economy and the Chinese economy would all benefit from the ensuing reduction in uncertainty. The signing of "phase I" will signal that both countries are willing to compromise and reach win-win outcomes.

In August the Chinese Central bank let the Yuan break the 7.0 mark in response to trade negotiations. Weakening the currency benefited exporters and counter-acted some of the effects of US tariffs. While drawing ire from the US, there were limited changes from Beijing.

It is more likely to stay between the range I have shown. It is little difficult to break 7.5 as it is suffering lot from US-China trade relations. However, it is unlikely to go below 7 as China is more and more distancing away from US in terms of bad effect as it it trying to find other markets.
